00:03:20.280 --> 00:03:22.060
For those who might
not know, can you

00:03:22.060 --> 00:03:24.910
please tell us what the story of
"Porgy and Bess" is all about?

00:03:24.910 --> 00:03:28.210
SUZAN-LORI PARKS: Yes. "Porgy
and Bess" is a love story.

00:03:28.210 --> 00:03:30.520
It's set in Catfish
Row, which is

00:03:30.520 --> 00:03:32.680
a neighborhood in
South Carolina.

00:03:32.680 --> 00:03:36.700
Now, the main action
concerns a man named Porgy.

00:03:36.700 --> 00:03:38.180
And he was born disabled.

00:03:38.180 --> 00:03:39.970
And because he was
born with a disability,

00:03:39.970 --> 00:03:43.910
he actually believes that God
has made him to be lonely,

00:03:43.910 --> 00:03:45.160
without love.

00:03:45.160 --> 00:03:46.580
And of course, he's wrong.

00:03:46.580 --> 00:03:50.040
Because into his life
comes love in the form

00:03:50.040 --> 00:03:51.440
of a woman named Bess.

00:03:51.440 --> 00:03:53.510
And "Porgy and Bess" is
also about the community

00:03:53.510 --> 00:03:54.220
of Catfish Row.

00:03:54.220 --> 00:03:57.500
And you get to meet the good
folks and the bad folks,

00:03:57.500 --> 00:04:00.960
the church going ladies
and the scallywag men.

00:04:00.960 --> 00:04:04.090
You get to see them
survive a hurricane.

00:04:04.090 --> 00:04:07.420
BTW, Bess happens
to be also involved

00:04:07.420 --> 00:04:09.530
with a guy called Crown.

00:04:09.530 --> 00:04:11.870
And so you get a little bit
of a love triangle going on

00:04:11.870 --> 00:04:12.804
in there.

00:04:12.804 --> 00:04:13.970
DIANE PAULUS: Lots of drama.

00:04:13.970 --> 00:04:16.070
SUZAN-LORI PARKS: Lots of drama.

00:04:16.070 --> 00:04:17.250
FEMALE SPEAKER: Thank you.

00:04:17.250 --> 00:04:19.349
And Diane, this is a
great American masterpiece

00:04:19.349 --> 00:04:21.450
with a significant history.

00:04:21.450 --> 00:04:24.131
Can you tell us a little
bit more about that history?

00:04:24.131 --> 00:04:24.880
DIANE PAULUS: Yes.

00:04:24.880 --> 00:04:29.560
This piece is a great
American masterwork.

00:04:29.560 --> 00:04:33.320
And it started as
a novel in 1925

00:04:33.320 --> 00:04:35.790
called "Porgy," written
by DuBose Heyward.

00:04:35.790 --> 00:04:40.600
It later became a play that
DuBose's wife Dorothy basically

00:04:40.600 --> 00:04:41.100
wrote.

00:04:41.100 --> 00:04:43.170
She encouraged her husband
to turn it into a play.

00:04:43.170 --> 00:04:44.711
They eventually
co-wrote it together.

00:04:44.711 --> 00:04:47.460
It premiered on
Broadway in 1927.

00:04:47.460 --> 00:04:50.360
George Gershwin was looking
for a subject matter

00:04:50.360 --> 00:04:52.440
to write his great
American folk opera.

00:04:52.440 --> 00:04:55.204
He famously read the novel
of "Porgy" in one sitting.

00:04:55.204 --> 00:04:56.870
Wrote George Gershwin
a letter and said,

00:04:56.870 --> 00:04:58.660
I want to turn
this into an opera.

00:04:58.660 --> 00:05:01.324
At the time, George Gershwin
said, oh, it's a play.

00:05:01.324 --> 00:05:02.740
It's having a
success on Broadway.

00:05:02.740 --> 00:05:04.640
So George patiently waited.

00:05:04.640 --> 00:05:07.330
And eventually, he
wrote it in 1935.

00:05:07.330 --> 00:05:09.690
He brought in his
brother, Ira Gershwin,

00:05:09.690 --> 00:05:12.930
who worked on the libretto and
the lyrics with DuBose Heyward.

00:05:12.930 --> 00:05:16.860
It premiered in Boston,
1935, then went to Broadway.

00:05:16.860 --> 00:05:18.995
So this piece actually
began on Broadway

00:05:18.995 --> 00:05:21.230
in the musical theater stage.

00:05:21.230 --> 00:05:24.040
There's an incredible piece of
history that I want to mention.

00:05:24.040 --> 00:05:29.140
In 1936, the original cast
goes on a very short tour.

00:05:29.140 --> 00:05:30.370
They go to Washington, DC.

00:05:30.370 --> 00:05:32.060
And they play at the
National Theatre.

00:05:32.060 --> 00:05:35.100
And of course, when they arrive,
the theater is segregated.

00:05:35.100 --> 00:05:37.740
So the original Porgy,
named Todd Duncan,

00:05:37.740 --> 00:05:39.580
said, well, this is a problem.

00:05:39.580 --> 00:05:42.382
We're not going to perform this
if this theater is segregated.

00:05:42.382 --> 00:05:44.090
And the producers at
the National Theatre

00:05:44.090 --> 00:05:45.887
said, well, that's
the way it is.

00:05:45.887 --> 00:05:46.720
He said, no, no, no.

00:05:46.720 --> 00:05:47.650
You don't understand.

00:05:47.650 --> 00:05:48.840
We're not going to perform.

00:05:48.840 --> 00:05:52.180
So the producers said, we
have a solution-- Wednesdays

00:05:52.180 --> 00:05:54.770
and Saturday matinees
for black people.

00:05:54.770 --> 00:05:57.630
And Todd Duncan said,
not good enough.

00:05:57.630 --> 00:06:01.750
And Anne Brown, who was the
original Bess, 19-year-old out

00:06:01.750 --> 00:06:03.959
of the Juilliard School,
had never acted in her life.

00:06:03.959 --> 00:06:05.458
George plucked her
out of Juilliard,

00:06:05.458 --> 00:06:06.870
took her into the show.

00:06:06.870 --> 00:06:09.304
She stood by Todd Duncan's side.

00:06:09.304 --> 00:06:10.720
Then the producers
at the National

00:06:10.720 --> 00:06:12.630
said, all right, we've
got another solution--

00:06:12.630 --> 00:06:15.180
the second half of the upper
balcony, for every performance,

00:06:15.180 --> 00:06:16.440
for black people.

00:06:16.440 --> 00:06:18.610
And Todd Duncan and Anne
Brown, and at this point,

00:06:18.610 --> 00:06:20.910
the whole cast said,
still not good enough.

00:06:20.910 --> 00:06:22.170
They got a little nervous.

00:06:22.170 --> 00:06:24.022
The producers, the cast
was being threatened

00:06:24.022 --> 00:06:25.730
to be fined for
breaching their contract.

00:06:25.730 --> 00:06:27.010
They wouldn't relent.

00:06:27.010 --> 00:06:29.660
And in March of 1936,
the National Theatre

00:06:29.660 --> 00:06:32.570
is desegregated for the
first time in its history,

00:06:32.570 --> 00:06:34.220
thanks to this production.

00:06:34.220 --> 00:06:35.528
So yes--

00:06:35.528 --> 00:06:40.110
[APPLAUSE]

00:06:40.110 --> 00:06:43.630
To me, that is why
I do the theater.

00:06:43.630 --> 00:06:45.220
It's not just what's
happening now.

00:06:45.220 --> 00:06:48.640
It's the history we come from,
and the fact that this work has

00:06:48.640 --> 00:06:51.450
had this long history
through the 20th century,

00:06:51.450 --> 00:06:53.980
onwards into the '50s,
with a production that

00:06:53.980 --> 00:06:56.270
tours Europe with
Leontyne Price,

00:06:56.270 --> 00:06:58.910
William Warfield, Cab Calloway.

00:06:58.910 --> 00:07:02.180
The young Maya Angelou was
a dancer in the chorus.

00:07:02.180 --> 00:07:05.130
Becomes a movie in 1959
with Sidney Poitier,

00:07:05.130 --> 00:07:08.060
Sammy Davis, Jr., eventually
touring opera houses

00:07:08.060 --> 00:07:09.360
all over the world.

00:07:09.360 --> 00:07:11.390
And then the great gift
of this production,

00:07:11.390 --> 00:07:14.340
to have incredible, contemporary
artists like Suzan-Lori

00:07:14.340 --> 00:07:17.430
Parks, Diedre Murray, our
choreographer, Ron Brown,

00:07:17.430 --> 00:07:19.650
and this phenomenal cast
that you'll meet today,

00:07:19.650 --> 00:07:22.530
who are bringing their
own humanity, their story,

00:07:22.530 --> 00:07:25.010
their integrity to
add another chapter

00:07:25.010 --> 00:07:26.720
to this incredible history.

00:07:26.720 --> 00:07:28.220
FEMALE SPEAKER: Thank you.

00:07:28.220 --> 00:07:30.717
And Michael, as the
nephew of Ira Gershwin,

00:07:30.717 --> 00:07:32.550
I'm sure you've seen
hundreds of productions

00:07:32.550 --> 00:07:34.150
of "Porgy and Bess."

00:07:34.150 --> 00:07:39.400
So tell us, what's different
about this Broadway production?

00:07:39.400 --> 00:07:41.150
MICHAEL STRUNSKY: Well,
Diane has told you

00:07:41.150 --> 00:07:44.170
all about the opera, the
development of the opera,

00:07:44.170 --> 00:07:46.440
starting in 1935.

00:07:46.440 --> 00:07:48.960
Well, the family
has come to realize

00:07:48.960 --> 00:07:53.320
that opera is a kind
of specialized taste.

00:07:53.320 --> 00:07:59.410
And "Porgy and Bess" has
such a wonderful universality

00:07:59.410 --> 00:08:03.500
that we wanted to find
a team and put together

00:08:03.500 --> 00:08:08.270
a team that could bring "Porgy
and Bess" back as a Broadway

00:08:08.270 --> 00:08:09.230
musical.

00:08:09.230 --> 00:08:13.210
And we picked this
lady here on my left.

00:08:13.210 --> 00:08:17.960
And what you're going to see and
what you're going to hear today

00:08:17.960 --> 00:08:21.900
is much more of the
Broadway musical version

00:08:21.900 --> 00:08:23.440
than the opera version.

00:08:23.440 --> 00:08:27.510
The Broadway musical
version is accessible.

00:08:27.510 --> 00:08:34.740
It has a tighter dramatic
structure than the opera.

00:08:34.740 --> 00:08:40.470
Yes, it doesn't have the highs
and lows of opera performance.

00:08:40.470 --> 00:08:42.970
But at the same
time, we have come

00:08:42.970 --> 00:08:46.990
to feel that this
is a gift that we

00:08:46.990 --> 00:08:51.090
hope the country and the
world will appreciate,

00:08:51.090 --> 00:08:53.490
that they can come
and see it in a more

00:08:53.490 --> 00:08:56.227
understandable and viable way.

00:08:56.227 --> 00:08:57.310
FEMALE SPEAKER: Thank you.

00:08:57.310 --> 00:08:59.970
And Diane, so this was
a musical on Broadway

00:08:59.970 --> 00:09:02.660
with a lot of incredible
dancing and choreography.

00:09:02.660 --> 00:09:06.270
Could you tell us about how
that works into the show?

00:09:06.270 --> 00:09:07.020
DIANE PAULUS: Yes.

00:09:07.020 --> 00:09:09.990
We have a great choreographer
named Ron Brown.

00:09:09.990 --> 00:09:12.330
And I think another
difference, often

00:09:12.330 --> 00:09:14.680
when this is done in
a big opera house,

00:09:14.680 --> 00:09:16.750
you have a separate
group of dancers

00:09:16.750 --> 00:09:18.360
who are doing the dancing.

00:09:18.360 --> 00:09:21.700
But in this production,
we have a tight ensemble.

00:09:21.700 --> 00:09:23.362
Everybody is doing everything.

00:09:23.362 --> 00:09:24.070
They are singing.

00:09:24.070 --> 00:09:24.736
They are acting.

00:09:24.736 --> 00:09:26.540
And they are dancing.

00:09:26.540 --> 00:09:30.030
And Ron's approach was, I think,
similar to all of our work

00:09:30.030 --> 00:09:34.240
on the show, was to really
build authentic expression.

00:09:34.240 --> 00:09:36.570
That it's not a
Broadway musical,

00:09:36.570 --> 00:09:39.640
here we go, five, six,
seven, eight, jazz hands.

00:09:39.640 --> 00:09:45.560
This is about character and
history and people's soul

00:09:45.560 --> 00:09:48.160
searching existence.

00:09:48.160 --> 00:09:50.980
And that was my quest
in the production.

00:09:50.980 --> 00:09:54.250
And it went everything,
for how we cast the show,

00:09:54.250 --> 00:09:56.950
how we did the costumes,
and how they move on stage.

00:09:56.950 --> 00:09:58.709
Every movement has meaning.

00:09:58.709 --> 00:09:59.500
And it's connected.

00:09:59.500 --> 00:10:00.875
SUZAN-LORI PARKS:
Can I just say,

00:10:00.875 --> 00:10:03.890
we won't see the dances
today, but the dancing

00:10:03.890 --> 00:10:05.135
is absolutely amazing.

00:10:05.135 --> 00:10:07.730
And I've seen the
show many, many times.

00:10:07.730 --> 00:10:10.677
I still cannot believe you
guys are dancing like you do

00:10:10.677 --> 00:10:12.885
on stage at the Golden Gate,
and singing brilliantly,

00:10:12.885 --> 00:10:15.050
and acting at the same time.

00:10:15.050 --> 00:10:17.809
I'm amazed.

00:10:17.809 --> 00:10:23.730
[APPLAUSE]

00:10:23.730 --> 00:10:25.844
FEMALE SPEAKER: And
finally, this version

00:10:25.844 --> 00:10:27.260
of "The Gershwins'
Porgy and Bess"

00:10:27.260 --> 00:10:30.490
has had an exciting
journey-- the world premiere

00:10:30.490 --> 00:10:33.540
at the American Repertory
Theater at Harvard University,

00:10:33.540 --> 00:10:37.280
followed by the Broadway
revival that won the 2012 Tony

00:10:37.280 --> 00:10:40.810
Award for Best Musical
Revival, pretty awesome.

00:10:40.810 --> 00:10:43.610
And so it won the Tony.

00:10:43.610 --> 00:10:45.530
So what is most exciting
out of all this?

00:10:45.530 --> 00:10:47.810
What is most exciting about
taking this production

00:10:47.810 --> 00:10:50.060
across the country?

00:10:50.060 --> 00:10:54.170
DIANE PAULUS: Well, first of
all, making theater is hard,

00:10:54.170 --> 00:10:55.550
like everything.

00:10:55.550 --> 00:10:56.800
And it takes time.

00:10:56.800 --> 00:11:00.897
And we have been on a journey
for years, building this show.

00:11:00.897 --> 00:11:02.230
And it's like making a painting.

00:11:02.230 --> 00:11:05.580
You just get to go in there
and deepen it and detail it

00:11:05.580 --> 00:11:07.200
and rediscover it.

00:11:07.200 --> 00:11:09.612
And here we are in 2013.

00:11:09.612 --> 00:11:10.445
The world's changed.

00:11:10.445 --> 00:11:14.680
We can kind of feel the show in
a new way with new performers.

00:11:14.680 --> 00:11:18.600
I think this tour, taking
the show out across America,

00:11:18.600 --> 00:11:21.890
is, to me, sort of the
pinnacle of this journey.

00:11:21.890 --> 00:11:24.170
Because this is an
American masterwork

00:11:24.170 --> 00:11:27.230
that belongs to
American audiences

00:11:27.230 --> 00:11:28.245
all across the country.

00:11:28.245 --> 00:11:29.120
I mean, it was great.

00:11:29.120 --> 00:11:30.120
We did it up at Harvard.

00:11:30.120 --> 00:11:31.680
Great we did it on Broadway.

00:11:31.680 --> 00:11:34.600
But every single person in every
little hometown across America

00:11:34.600 --> 00:11:38.430
should be able to see
this show and say, yes, I

00:11:38.430 --> 00:11:40.020
understand the story.

00:11:40.020 --> 00:11:46.472
I relate to this struggle,
to this love, and to know it.

00:11:46.472 --> 00:11:47.930
Not just people
who know the opera,

00:11:47.930 --> 00:11:50.510
but for young people,
that's what's touched me,

00:11:50.510 --> 00:11:54.570
is that a young generation can
now say, George Gershwin, wow.

00:11:54.570 --> 00:11:55.860
He's good.

00:11:55.860 --> 00:11:58.640
And those lyrics, Ira and
DuBose, those are pretty good.

00:11:58.640 --> 00:11:59.390
And you know what?

00:11:59.390 --> 00:12:02.490
That's our American
cultural history

00:12:02.490 --> 00:12:05.760
that we need to educate
and give to people so they

00:12:05.760 --> 00:12:07.334
can own it and be proud of it.

00:12:07.334 --> 00:12:08.250
FEMALE SPEAKER: Great.

00:12:08.250 --> 00:12:08.750
Thank you.

00:12:08.750 --> 00:12:10.170
Thank you guys.

00:12:10.170 --> 00:12:12.940
So I'd now like to welcome
Nathaniel Stampley and Alicia

00:12:12.940 --> 00:12:17.000
Hall Moran, who play Porgy and
Bess, to perform "Bess, You

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:18.714
Is My Woman Now."

00:12:18.714 --> 00:12:22.420
[APPLAUSE]

00:12:22.420 --> 00:12:23.961
[MUSIC - "BESS, YOU
IS MY WOMAN NOW"]

00:17:20.862 --> 00:17:34.806
[APPLAUSE]

00:17:34.806 --> 00:17:35.940
FEMALE SPEAKER: Thank you.

00:17:35.940 --> 00:17:37.340
That was so beautiful.

00:17:37.340 --> 00:17:39.030
That was so great.

00:17:39.030 --> 00:17:40.000
Thank you.

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:42.620
So you guys play Porgy and Bess.

00:17:42.620 --> 00:17:47.110
Can you tell us, who are the
characters of Porgy and Bess?

00:17:47.110 --> 00:17:48.790
NATHANIEL STAMPLEY:
Well, Porgy and Bess

00:17:48.790 --> 00:17:53.250
are two people that probably
wouldn't normally be together.

00:17:53.250 --> 00:17:57.840
And through the course of
the show and this story,

00:17:57.840 --> 00:18:01.100
some extraordinary events
happen that bring them together.

00:18:01.100 --> 00:18:03.940
And they truly are each
other's true loves.

00:18:03.940 --> 00:18:08.290
And so once they're together,
their lives completely change.

00:18:08.290 --> 00:18:11.310
They become really
different people.

00:18:11.310 --> 00:18:14.740
And so it's wonderful to take
this journey every single night

00:18:14.740 --> 00:18:15.922
with Alicia.

00:18:15.922 --> 00:18:18.200
ALICIA HALL MORAN:
And Suzan-Lori Parks

00:18:18.200 --> 00:18:22.490
helped encourage us to
understand these characters as

00:18:22.490 --> 00:18:27.840
essential as Romeo and
Juliet, Tristan and Isolde.

00:18:27.840 --> 00:18:34.689
These are two Americans
in love, in English.

00:18:34.689 --> 00:18:37.527
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:37.527 --> 00:18:38.950
FEMALE SPEAKER: Thank you.

00:18:38.950 --> 00:18:41.540
And how did you
guys work to develop

00:18:41.540 --> 00:18:44.805
both your individual characters
and their relationship?

00:18:47.420 --> 00:18:50.230
ALICIA HALL MORAN:
Bess is a fiery woman

00:18:50.230 --> 00:18:53.990
who often finds herself
on the outside of things.

00:18:53.990 --> 00:18:57.990
And I don't have any
difficulty understanding

00:18:57.990 --> 00:18:59.598
that point of view.

00:18:59.598 --> 00:19:00.098
[LAUGHTER]

00:19:00.098 --> 00:19:02.870
I had a really
lovely upbringing.

00:19:02.870 --> 00:19:06.020
So I think that for
me, all of the work

00:19:06.020 --> 00:19:10.540
has been in understanding
kind of that emotional

00:19:10.540 --> 00:19:13.360
disenfranchisement,
and really trying

00:19:13.360 --> 00:19:17.640
to be more honest to
the humanity of it,

00:19:17.640 --> 00:19:23.740
to resist mean mugging, to
resist feeling that there's

00:19:23.740 --> 00:19:30.140
something dirty about being
unqualified for a moment.

