00:32:08.740 --> 00:32:10.650
coming from the
previous productions,

00:32:10.650 --> 00:32:13.360
and also, now this
cast are veterans,

00:32:13.360 --> 00:32:15.700
because they had a rehearsal
process in New York

00:32:15.700 --> 00:32:17.140
together, shared.

00:32:17.140 --> 00:32:21.920
Really knowing the inner tracks
of the ensemble as well as we

00:32:21.920 --> 00:32:24.340
do, we understand
the real strength

00:32:24.340 --> 00:32:26.690
that Porgy gains is
from the community.

00:32:26.690 --> 00:32:28.950
The real strength
that Bess will find

00:32:28.950 --> 00:32:33.380
when she's redeemed-- oh,
she messes it up by the end.

00:32:33.380 --> 00:32:36.680
But they come for
her, to heal her,

00:32:36.680 --> 00:32:39.750
and to give your body weight
to the women in the cast.

00:32:39.750 --> 00:32:43.740
Or Sporting Life slithering
all over you, only Mariah

00:32:43.740 --> 00:32:45.270
could prevent that.

00:32:45.270 --> 00:32:46.750
And he gets rid of her.

00:32:46.750 --> 00:32:49.880
So we really
understand that you're

00:32:49.880 --> 00:32:52.880
going to get through the
day with the actual actors.

00:32:52.880 --> 00:32:54.510
But the characters
are going to make it

00:32:54.510 --> 00:32:57.300
through because of
the actual community.

00:32:57.300 --> 00:32:59.400
And we represent
a new era of that.

00:32:59.400 --> 00:33:01.700
Because we know what
they're pulling.

00:33:01.700 --> 00:33:03.680
And it's crazy good.

00:33:03.680 --> 00:33:04.750
I love your question.

00:33:04.750 --> 00:33:06.024
Thank you so much.

00:33:06.024 --> 00:33:08.440
AUDIENCE: I'd like to hear a
little more about the process

00:33:08.440 --> 00:33:12.680
of adapting the production
to what you call a Broadway

00:33:12.680 --> 00:33:15.410
musical version as opposed
to the opera version?

00:33:15.410 --> 00:33:19.165
There's the staging, there's
the music, there's the story.

00:33:19.165 --> 00:33:20.650
I'd like to hear
more about that.

00:33:20.650 --> 00:33:25.120
DIANE PAULUS: I think if the
opera is done uncut, which

00:33:25.120 --> 00:33:29.570
sometimes it's done, it clocks
in at well over four hours.

00:33:29.570 --> 00:33:33.330
So I think we knew we wanted
to make a version that really

00:33:33.330 --> 00:33:39.060
retained the incredible
score, that told the story as

00:33:39.060 --> 00:33:43.530
specifically and as
truthfully as we could.

00:33:43.530 --> 00:33:45.770
But we wanted to just
like close up on it.

00:33:45.770 --> 00:33:53.800
We wanted to make it intimate
and focused and theatrical.

00:33:53.800 --> 00:33:57.740
So of course, our production
is like 2 and 1/2 hours.

00:33:57.740 --> 00:33:59.200
So you're looking at cuts.

00:33:59.200 --> 00:34:00.906
And George and Ira made cuts.

00:34:00.906 --> 00:34:02.780
The first night after
it premiered in Boston,

00:34:02.780 --> 00:34:03.840
they cut out 45 minutes.

00:34:03.840 --> 00:34:08.929
So you're going from guides from
the original authors of options

00:34:08.929 --> 00:34:10.190
of things to cut.

00:34:10.190 --> 00:34:14.389
And Suzan-Lori and Diedre Murray
and myself and our music team,

00:34:14.389 --> 00:34:16.870
our conductor and our
associate, we spent,

00:34:16.870 --> 00:34:19.770
I'd say, at least
one year going bar

00:34:19.770 --> 00:34:22.510
by bar through
that entire score,

00:34:22.510 --> 00:34:25.570
laboriously figuring
out how to make the cut,

00:34:25.570 --> 00:34:28.000
how to continue
the musical line.

00:34:28.000 --> 00:34:29.110
What is necessary?

00:34:29.110 --> 00:34:33.360
What maybe could we take
out to strengthen something,

00:34:33.360 --> 00:34:36.550
to make it even more
kind of immediate?

00:34:36.550 --> 00:34:41.068
So it was an incredible process,
a careful, careful process.

00:34:41.068 --> 00:34:43.960
SUZAN-LORI PARKS: Yeah, maybe
a chunk might have been cut.

00:34:43.960 --> 00:34:48.960
And then add a few words here
to make the character arc

00:34:48.960 --> 00:34:53.170
stronger, a lot of
basic dramaturgical,

00:34:53.170 --> 00:34:56.909
architectural work to track
each of these characters.

00:34:56.909 --> 00:34:59.290
Each and every one of
these main characters

00:34:59.290 --> 00:35:02.460
has a very, very strong
and definite character arc.

00:35:02.460 --> 00:35:07.270
And sometimes, we might
cut a character out,

00:35:07.270 --> 00:35:09.400
a minor character, and
replaced him or her

00:35:09.400 --> 00:35:11.690
with one of the main
characters to carry that story

00:35:11.690 --> 00:35:13.546
line through.

00:35:13.546 --> 00:35:15.670
AUDIENCE: "Summertime" got
rearranged a little bit,

00:35:15.670 --> 00:35:17.020
to have an extra singer in it.

00:35:17.020 --> 00:35:20.074
So was there much of that
kind of change, as well?

00:35:20.074 --> 00:35:21.490
DIANE PAULUS:
Definitely, thinking

00:35:21.490 --> 00:35:24.520
about how to tell the story.

00:35:24.520 --> 00:35:27.380
And I think the point that
Sumayya and David were making,

00:35:27.380 --> 00:35:31.040
that this idea-- you know,
people hear "Summertime."

00:35:31.040 --> 00:35:34.160
And you kind of
go, oh, that hit.

00:35:34.160 --> 00:35:36.640
Or, oh, Fantasia sang that.

00:35:36.640 --> 00:35:39.710
So our production's like,
no, no, look at the story.

00:35:39.710 --> 00:35:43.580
Look at what the song
means, with Daddy and Mama

00:35:43.580 --> 00:35:44.320
standing by.

00:35:44.320 --> 00:35:46.470
And there you can see
that daddy and mama

00:35:46.470 --> 00:35:48.150
looking over their baby.

00:35:48.150 --> 00:35:52.230
So every choice was
driven by the story,

00:35:52.230 --> 00:35:54.059
to really intensify the story.

00:35:54.059 --> 00:35:56.350
SUZAN-LORI PARKS: I just want
to say an exciting thing.

00:35:56.350 --> 00:35:58.710
You see Jake and Clara
singing this wonderful song

00:35:58.710 --> 00:36:00.290
to their child at the top.

00:36:00.290 --> 00:36:03.610
And then if you know the show
already, or if you've seen it,

00:36:03.610 --> 00:36:07.626
or if you might see it, watch
for when it gets reprised.

00:36:07.626 --> 00:36:08.750
And that's in the original.

00:36:08.750 --> 00:36:10.552
But watch how that
songs gets reprised.

00:36:10.552 --> 00:36:12.760
And remember the first time
you heard it in the show,

00:36:12.760 --> 00:36:15.540
and the meaning that it takes on
as we travel through the show,

00:36:15.540 --> 00:36:17.956
and the other things going on
on stage, especially when we

00:36:17.956 --> 00:36:19.230
hear it the last time.

00:36:19.230 --> 00:36:20.000
What is going on?

00:36:20.000 --> 00:36:21.500
DIANE PAULUS: It's
sung three times.

00:36:21.500 --> 00:36:24.680
And the tragic thing is,
those two characters die.

00:36:24.680 --> 00:36:25.690
So you start the show.

00:36:25.690 --> 00:36:27.509
And if you know the
story, it's almost

00:36:27.509 --> 00:36:28.800
like you almost can't watch it.

00:36:28.800 --> 00:36:31.310
It's just like, all the
hope in that moment.

00:36:31.310 --> 00:36:33.410
But again, as Alicia
was saying, you

00:36:33.410 --> 00:36:36.450
see how the community
rises up through it.

00:36:36.450 --> 00:36:44.380
It's that uplifting growth
admits terrible adversity

00:36:44.380 --> 00:36:45.844
and tragedy.

00:36:45.844 --> 00:36:47.260
MICHAEL STRUNSKY:
One thing that's

00:36:47.260 --> 00:36:49.510
true about this is
that the emphasis here

00:36:49.510 --> 00:36:55.310
has been on story, just as
any good theatrical piece has

00:36:55.310 --> 00:36:57.210
to respect story.

00:36:57.210 --> 00:37:01.860
And we've taken,
Diane and Suzan-Lori

00:37:01.860 --> 00:37:05.960
have taken that as a charge.

00:37:05.960 --> 00:37:08.670
And I believe they've solved it
really, really magnificently.

00:37:11.932 --> 00:37:14.570
SUZAN-LORI PARKS: I always
like hearing you say that.

00:37:14.570 --> 00:37:16.010
[LAUGHTER]

00:37:16.010 --> 00:37:18.410
I never get tired of that.

00:37:18.410 --> 00:37:19.250
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:37:19.250 --> 00:37:22.250
I am completely in awe that I'm
in the same room as Suzan-Lori

00:37:22.250 --> 00:37:23.390
Parks and Diane Paulus.

00:37:23.390 --> 00:37:26.749
Actually, I'm a graduate
of the ART in 2006.

00:37:26.749 --> 00:37:28.290
Sadly, I missed you,
because you have

00:37:28.290 --> 00:37:30.520
been doing amazing
work there, amazing.

00:37:30.520 --> 00:37:31.580
It's so impressive.

00:37:31.580 --> 00:37:36.050
And my question is
actually two things.

00:37:36.050 --> 00:37:41.210
How is it that you, A, came
upon this play or musical,

00:37:41.210 --> 00:37:42.630
that you wanted to revive it.

00:37:42.630 --> 00:37:47.190
And two, how is it that you have
created, in many of your works,

00:37:47.190 --> 00:37:52.949
somehow found the balance of
artistry and audience appeal

00:37:52.949 --> 00:37:54.990
in such a way that you
make-- obviously, audience

00:37:54.990 --> 00:37:57.992
keep coming back and loving
everything that you've done.

00:37:57.992 --> 00:37:58.950
Where do you find that?

00:37:58.950 --> 00:38:00.629
Because it doesn't
seem to me like

00:38:00.629 --> 00:38:02.670
you've sacrificed any
artistry in any of the work

00:38:02.670 --> 00:38:04.302
that you've done.

00:38:04.302 --> 00:38:06.760
DIANE PAULUS: Well, I'll answer
your second question first.

00:38:06.760 --> 00:38:08.760
I believe in the audience.

00:38:08.760 --> 00:38:11.400
I believe audiences are smart.

00:38:11.400 --> 00:38:13.020
They want to be challenged.

00:38:13.020 --> 00:38:15.090
They want to feel.

00:38:15.090 --> 00:38:18.900
I think it's a very generous
act, an audience, in this day

00:38:18.900 --> 00:38:22.030
and age, when we're all so
busy, to come out of our lives

00:38:22.030 --> 00:38:25.410
and be live in a room together.

00:38:25.410 --> 00:38:28.830
So we have an obligation
to meet that audience.

00:38:28.830 --> 00:38:30.800
And that's where I
start as a director.

00:38:30.800 --> 00:38:33.590
It's really not about like,
my art, what I want to do.

00:38:33.590 --> 00:38:36.330
No, I think, why
tell the story now?

00:38:36.330 --> 00:38:37.390
What's the event?

00:38:37.390 --> 00:38:39.400
What can we communicate?

00:38:39.400 --> 00:38:42.400
Why should an audience bother
to come see "Porgy and Bess"?

00:38:42.400 --> 00:38:43.920
That's where I start.

00:38:43.920 --> 00:38:48.280
And rather that being
distracting or pandering,

00:38:48.280 --> 00:38:51.350
it's actually the catalyst
for me as a director.

00:38:51.350 --> 00:38:52.442
And that's the theater.

00:38:52.442 --> 00:38:54.150
I mean, when you work
in the theater now,

00:38:54.150 --> 00:38:57.190
you really have to think, what
is the theater as a medium?

00:38:57.190 --> 00:38:59.700
It is about live transmission.

00:38:59.700 --> 00:39:03.720
It can only happen in the
presence of an audience.

00:39:03.720 --> 00:39:06.350
Not a lot of other
artistic mediums

00:39:06.350 --> 00:39:10.380
are that dependent on the
living, breathing moment.

00:39:10.380 --> 00:39:12.936
And I think in our day and age,
to feel present and alive--

00:39:12.936 --> 00:39:14.310
I mean, it was a
question of you,

00:39:14.310 --> 00:39:18.037
all saying about being in
the moment, that's a gift.

00:39:18.037 --> 00:39:19.870
I mean, that's why I
love doing the theater.

00:39:19.870 --> 00:39:21.950
It's like, rehearsal,
you're in the moment,

00:39:21.950 --> 00:39:23.320
to come into a room.

00:39:23.320 --> 00:39:25.640
And that's, I think,
what an audience craves.

00:39:25.640 --> 00:39:26.902
You forget the past.

00:39:26.902 --> 00:39:28.360
You stop thinking
about the future.

00:39:28.360 --> 00:39:31.900
And you are in the
present, emotionally,

00:39:31.900 --> 00:39:35.860
psychically with
these characters.

00:39:35.860 --> 00:39:38.400
And this is a piece
that allows you

00:39:38.400 --> 00:39:40.520
to go deep, as Kingsley said.

00:39:40.520 --> 00:39:43.940
So when I was approached by the
Gershwin estates and the DuBose

00:39:43.940 --> 00:39:47.590
Heyward estates, would you
be interested in this charge

00:39:47.590 --> 00:39:48.880
that Mike said?

00:39:48.880 --> 00:39:50.300
We know it exists as an opera.

00:39:50.300 --> 00:39:51.841
And it will always
exist as an opera.

00:39:51.841 --> 00:39:54.230
But what about
creating a version that

00:39:54.230 --> 00:39:56.360
really celebrates
it as a musical?

00:39:56.360 --> 00:39:58.170
Would you want to do that?

00:39:58.170 --> 00:40:00.910
And what writer would
you like to work with?

00:40:00.910 --> 00:40:03.360
That really came
from the estates.

00:40:03.360 --> 00:40:07.410
That was a huge sign to
me of the willingness

00:40:07.410 --> 00:40:12.630
to really make this feel
relevant to our lives today.

00:40:12.630 --> 00:40:14.380
And working with
Suzan-Lori, I was

00:40:14.380 --> 00:40:15.630
dying to work with this lady.

00:40:15.630 --> 00:40:16.296
Are you kidding?

00:40:16.296 --> 00:40:17.360
She's a genius.

00:40:17.360 --> 00:40:19.970
And her dramaturgical
mind is so strong.

00:40:19.970 --> 00:40:20.630
[APPLAUSE]

00:40:20.630 --> 00:40:24.800
This experience
of creating this,

00:40:24.800 --> 00:40:28.250
and then, it's about them.

00:40:28.250 --> 00:40:30.865
The art of a director is,
I know something about it.

00:40:30.865 --> 00:40:32.490
Suzan-Lori, we know
something about it.

00:40:32.490 --> 00:40:35.022
But then it transfers
to the cast.

00:40:35.022 --> 00:40:37.230
And that's how they get
through every night, I think.

00:40:37.230 --> 00:40:38.510
Because they are
telling the story.

00:40:38.510 --> 00:40:40.510
They are the keepers of
the torch and the flame.

00:40:40.510 --> 00:40:44.670
And they are holding that
much more than us now.

00:40:44.670 --> 00:40:45.820
We've given it.

00:40:45.820 --> 00:40:47.012
We've raised the baby.

00:40:47.012 --> 00:40:49.470
And then the baby has to go
out in the world, in this case,

00:40:49.470 --> 00:40:50.095
across America.

00:40:53.430 --> 00:40:55.400
AUDIENCE: I know you
mentioned briefly

00:40:55.400 --> 00:40:56.680
Leontyne Price and that tour.

00:40:56.680 --> 00:40:59.380
And I think you were
referring to the 1955 tour

00:40:59.380 --> 00:41:00.550
to the Eastern Bloc.

00:41:00.550 --> 00:41:01.870
So I know that was a huge deal.

00:41:01.870 --> 00:41:04.580
Because that was the
first American musical

00:41:04.580 --> 00:41:08.401
or American opera that came to
USSR and all those countries.

00:41:08.401 --> 00:41:10.900
And I know they had a different
message to spread back then.

00:41:10.900 --> 00:41:14.250
But I'm wondering, if you
had the opportunity now,

00:41:14.250 --> 00:41:16.620
maybe you will,
where would you take

00:41:16.620 --> 00:41:18.050
this production in the world?

00:41:18.050 --> 00:41:19.610
And what kind of
message would you

00:41:19.610 --> 00:41:22.530
want to say now, as
opposed to back then?

00:41:22.530 --> 00:41:24.120
MICHAEL STRUNSKY:
Well, I'm not sure

00:41:24.120 --> 00:41:26.890
that the message is anything
more than what you see.

00:41:26.890 --> 00:41:29.070
The message is there.

00:41:29.070 --> 00:41:34.290
It's truth, and what
Suzan-Lori and the rest

00:41:34.290 --> 00:41:39.030
of the creative cast believe
that community was like.

00:41:39.030 --> 00:41:43.110
And yes, we're open to
taking-- a matter of fact,

00:41:43.110 --> 00:41:45.400
we are doing a
production in London

00:41:45.400 --> 00:41:48.790
at the outdoor theater
there this coming summer.

00:41:52.094 --> 00:41:54.230
SUZAN-LORI PARKS: I
think what's wonderful

00:41:54.230 --> 00:41:58.230
about this production is
that while our work on it

00:41:58.230 --> 00:42:00.440
was, or my work on
it was dramaturgical

00:42:00.440 --> 00:42:03.450
and architectural,
I think what happens

00:42:03.450 --> 00:42:05.740
is, in this day
and age, there is

00:42:05.740 --> 00:42:08.620
a political component
that we can't escape.

00:42:08.620 --> 00:42:14.730
And that is as simple as people
of African descent are people.

00:42:14.730 --> 00:42:15.950
We are people.

00:42:15.950 --> 00:42:18.720
And I think that is
dovetailed exactly

00:42:18.720 --> 00:42:21.449
hand in glove with the
message, if you will,

00:42:21.449 --> 00:42:23.490
of the very first production
of "Porgy and Bess."

00:42:23.490 --> 00:42:26.760
I think that's what Mr.
Gershwin's and the Heywards

00:42:26.760 --> 00:42:27.719
were saying.

00:42:27.719 --> 00:42:30.260
I think that's what it said when
we went to the Eastern Bloc.

00:42:30.260 --> 00:42:32.390
And that's the beauty
of this country,

00:42:32.390 --> 00:42:35.610
that we can say that
about all of us.

00:42:35.610 --> 00:42:38.080
We are all in it together.

00:42:38.080 --> 00:42:40.200
And when we take that
and we go abroad,

00:42:40.200 --> 00:42:43.140
or we go just to various cities
around the United States,

00:42:43.140 --> 00:42:45.150
we are all in it together.

00:42:45.150 --> 00:42:46.060
Hello.

00:42:46.060 --> 00:42:48.180
And when we go abroad
and take that message,

00:42:48.180 --> 00:42:50.940
we are all in this together,
that is a very powerful message

00:42:50.940 --> 00:42:54.200
for the world, to remember
that it's all of us

00:42:54.200 --> 00:42:55.610
together in here.

00:42:55.610 --> 00:42:58.341
So it's good stuff.

00:42:58.341 --> 00:43:00.209
[APPLAUSE]

00:43:00.209 --> 00:43:03.011
FEMALE SPEAKER: One more
question, one last question.

00:43:03.011 --> 00:43:07.300
AUDIENCE: I have a question for
Sporting Life, Porgy, and Bess.

00:43:07.300 --> 00:43:11.750
Individually, do you think your
characters would have liked

00:43:11.750 --> 00:43:15.050
to have seen a sequel
to Porgy and Bess?

00:43:15.050 --> 00:43:21.900
And to Michael, do you know if
your Uncle Ira and George, had

00:43:21.900 --> 00:43:24.130
he lived, had planned a sequel?

00:43:26.760 --> 00:43:28.670
MICHAEL STRUNSKY:
Not that I know of.

00:43:28.670 --> 00:43:32.430
And I guess emotionally, I
would very much doubt it.

00:43:32.430 --> 00:43:35.950
They had plenty of
other things to do.

00:43:35.950 --> 00:43:40.994
[LAUGHTER]

00:43:40.994 --> 00:43:43.410
NATHANIEL STAMPLEY: I'll just
say, in this day and age now

00:43:43.410 --> 00:43:49.200
of prequels, I'm actually
more interested in that, this

00:43:49.200 --> 00:43:52.550
before story.

00:43:52.550 --> 00:43:57.780
And the way that this
production is put together,

00:43:57.780 --> 00:44:02.130
it really is up to the audience
to decide what happens.

00:44:02.130 --> 00:44:06.120
And I think that's where,
as actors and audience,

00:44:06.120 --> 00:44:07.870
we're all in the
same room, that's

00:44:07.870 --> 00:44:10.400
one point where we
all get together.

00:44:10.400 --> 00:44:11.066
You decide.

00:44:11.066 --> 00:44:13.440
Everyone walks out of the
theater with different answers.

00:44:13.440 --> 00:44:15.850
So at the stage
door, I enjoy to hear

00:44:15.850 --> 00:44:19.464
what happens with
Porgy and Bess.

00:44:19.464 --> 00:44:21.130
ALICIA HALL MORAN: I
love this question.

00:44:21.130 --> 00:44:23.550
Because you're going to hear
our personalities in how

00:44:23.550 --> 00:44:25.820
we answer it.

00:44:25.820 --> 00:44:29.530
So his idea would
make money with before

00:44:29.530 --> 00:44:31.350
and a blockbuster after.

00:44:31.350 --> 00:44:36.540
And my idea is kind of that
it's being presented as a fable,

00:44:36.540 --> 00:44:39.350
in a sense, in the original,
and in the way it's

00:44:39.350 --> 00:44:41.080
been recreated here.

00:44:41.080 --> 00:44:43.130
So that just like
Diane said, it's

00:44:43.130 --> 00:44:46.830
heartbreaking when the young,
beautiful couple comes out

00:44:46.830 --> 00:44:49.980
for "Summertime"
with their baby.

00:44:49.980 --> 00:44:58.130
Because you know by the end, and
the harlot is holding the baby.

00:44:58.130 --> 00:45:02.450
Man, oh, man, that's
the cycle-- the baby,

00:45:02.450 --> 00:45:05.220
the birth, the birth
of something else.

00:45:05.220 --> 00:45:07.810
It's going to go well for you,
or it's going to go badly.

00:45:07.810 --> 00:45:10.840
You kind of get another
shot at it the next day

00:45:10.840 --> 00:45:11.860
in the next show.

00:45:11.860 --> 00:45:15.530
So I think we are, each
of us, are everyone.

00:45:15.530 --> 00:45:19.620
Not an every man, so much,
specifically in the narrative

00:45:19.620 --> 00:45:25.200
structure, but like Aesop's
Fables, there's no before.

00:45:25.200 --> 00:45:26.290
There's no after.

00:45:26.290 --> 00:45:27.540
It's its own universe.

00:45:27.540 --> 00:45:29.290
You're going to be the
dinosaur this time,

00:45:29.290 --> 00:45:31.895
and the monkey next
time, that kind of idea.

00:45:31.895 --> 00:45:34.400
And I know there's no
dinosaurs in Aesop's.

00:45:34.400 --> 00:45:37.415
Don't get all technical with me.

00:45:37.415 --> 00:45:43.720
[LAUGHTER]

00:45:43.720 --> 00:45:46.730
KINGLSEY LEGGS:
That was awesome.

00:45:46.730 --> 00:45:47.680
I agree with Nate.

00:45:47.680 --> 00:45:51.310
I think what's extraordinary
about this piece is

00:45:51.310 --> 00:45:54.360
that it's not wrapped
up in a bow at the end.

00:45:54.360 --> 00:45:57.770
And it allows everyone to have
their own interpretation of,

00:45:57.770 --> 00:45:59.800
how does the story end?

00:45:59.800 --> 00:46:02.212
How do you think it ends?

00:46:02.212 --> 00:46:03.420
How would you like it to end?

00:46:03.420 --> 00:46:06.220
And I think that's
wonderful for everyone.

00:46:06.220 --> 00:46:11.490
I think probably the dying
question for everyone is,

00:46:11.490 --> 00:46:13.504
does he find her in New York?

00:46:13.504 --> 00:46:14.670
Does he make it to New York?

00:46:14.670 --> 00:46:18.810
Does he find her in New York?

00:46:18.810 --> 00:46:21.930
But I really feel that
it's best the way it is.

00:46:21.930 --> 00:46:24.550
It's best that we don't know.

00:46:24.550 --> 00:46:27.800
I think that goes along with the
message and the spirit of what

00:46:27.800 --> 00:46:30.530
the piece is.

00:46:30.530 --> 00:46:32.712
FEMALE SPEAKER: Thank you.

